def: Curved and sharppointed, like a falcula, or claw of a falcon.
A fossil coral of the genus Heliolites, having twelve-rayedcells. It is found in the Silurian rocks.
The ventral plate of the prothorax of an insect.

from Sing, v. Singing bird. (Zoöl.) (a) Popularly, any birdthat sings; a song bird. (b) Specifically, any one of the Oscines.-- Singing book, a book containing music for singing; a book oftunes.-- Singing falcon or hawk. (Zoöl.) See Chanting falcon, underChanting.-- Singing fish (Zoöl.), a California toadfish (Porichthysporosissimus).-- Singing flame (Acoustics), a flame, as of hydrogen or coal gas,burning within a tube and so adjusted as to set the air within thetube in vibration, causing sound. The apparatus is called alsochemical harmonicon.-- Singing master, a man who teaches vocal music.-- Singing school, a school in which persons are instructed insinging.
To be suspicious of; to have suspicion. [Obs.]I do not misdoubt my wife. Shak.
Resembling a hector; blustering; insolent; taunting. "Hectorly,ruffianlike swaggering or huffing." Barrow.
A person who disseizes another of lands which the disseizee hadbefore recovered of the same disseizor. Blackstone.
The act of clearing land of forests. Daniel.
The doctrine and usages of Episcopalians; episcopacy.
In honor of Apollo; as, the Apollinarian games.
